          <h2>assemblr</h2>
          <p>A social network for the GA community.<span style="font-size: 0.8em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4); display: block; text-align: justify;">This application was my third project at General Assembly and my first group project.  Team members were <%= link_to "Kevin Yang", "https://github.com/kyangy", target: '_blank' %> and <%= link_to "Jonathan Thomas Fung", "https://github.com/jonathanth0mas/", target: '_blank' %>. The site was built with Rails 4, PostgreSQL, RSpec, Factory Girl, and CircleCI for integrated testing. The original version of the project integrated the Linkedin API: we allowed users to log in with their LinkedIn credentials and populate their General Assemblr profile page with their photo, positions, education, etc. The project provided a valuable lesson about <%= link_to "not relying too heavily on 3rd party APIs", "http://techcrunch.com/2015/02/12/linkedin-battens-down-the-hatches-on-api-use-limiting-full-access-to-partners/#TRjtal:1Z2G", target: '_blank' %>. Version 2, which I am currently working on, will allow users to display their favorite Github repos and also to connect to Codewars directly from our application site. However, I am integrating these APIs in a way that will enhance the application if present, but will not break the application in the event that the permissions change.  I will link to the updates here.</span></p>
